2 Introduction

An attempt to learn text mining using Boris Johnson’s televised address on May 10th 2020.

Data: https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pm-address-to-the-nation-on-coronavirus-10-may-2020

Methods draw very heavily on https://www.tidytextmining.com (Text Mining with R: A Tidy Approach, Julia Silge and David Robinson, 2020-03-07)

3 The data

A relatively short speech/address of 94 sentences outlining the framework for easing UK (actually English) lockdown.

nWords <- nrow(tidy_df)
nWordsReduced <- nrow(reduced_df)

kableExtra::kable(head(df), caption = "First 6 sentences") %>% kable_styling()
Table 3.1: First 6 sentences
line
It is now almost two months since the people of this country began to put up with restrictions on their freedom – your freedom – of a kind that we have never seen before in peace or war.
And you have shown the good sense to support those rules overwhelmingly.
You have put up with all the hardships of that programme of social distancing.
Because you understand that as things stand, and as the experience of every other country has shown, it’s the only way to defeat the coronavirus - the most vicious threat this country has faced in my lifetime.
And though the death toll has been tragic, and the suffering immense.
And though we grieve for all those we have lost.

The address used a total of 1972 different words of which 619 were non-stopping words (if, and, the etc)

4 Word frequency by postive/negative sentiment

We use the bing sentiment data to assign sentiment (positive vs negative) to each non-stopping word used and calculate the frequency.

Figure 4.1 shows the frequency of these words by sentiment.

bing_word_countsPlot

Figure 4.1: Frequency of words by sentiment

Figure 4.2 shows a word cloud of these words by sentiment.

# for some reson we can't capture this as a plot in the R script?
wc <- reduced_df %>% inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>% count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    reshape2::acast(word ~ sentiment, value.var = "n", fill = 0)

wordcloud::comparison.cloud(wc, colors = c("gray80", "gray20"), max.words = 100)

Figure 4.2: Wordcloud of words by sentiment

5 Frequency of sentiment by line

Figure 5.1 shows the number of positive/negative words by line (sentence) number. As we can see there are positive words at the very start followed by negative words, then a mix and then a positive finale.

sentimentByLinePLot

Figure 5.1: Frequency of entiment by line number
